## Docs and harness sync

When **a plan or implementation slice is finished** (user confirms completion, or you deliver the last planned step), **or** when the user **asks you to make commits** (or prepare a commit / PR):

**Before every commit** — Run linting (and each touched stack’s usual static checks, e.g. `mypy`) for **all** areas your diff touches; fix failures before committing unless the user explicitly approves an exception. Match what CI runs for that stack (see [`.github/workflows/ci.yml`](../../.github/workflows/ci.yml) for **`fitness-backend`**: `ruff check .`, `mypy app`, `pytest` from `fitness-backend/`).

### Formatting and front-end (when added)

If a **web** (or other Node) package is added and CI introduces **Prettier** or similar, run the same commands CI uses on paths your diff touches (e.g. `npx prettier --write` / `--check` from that package root). **Do not rely on ESLint alone** where Prettier is enforced. Until then, backend formatting is covered by **Ruff** as configured in `fitness-backend`.

1. **Keep runbooks accurate** — After substantive changes, ensure **commands and rules only** stay current where this repo documents them: primarily [`fitness-backend/README.md`](../../fitness-backend/README.md) for backend run/lint/test; [`.agent-harness/CLAUDE.md`](../../.agent-harness/CLAUDE.md) for harness role constraints and `harness` commands. If the project adds a root or subproject **`CLAUDE.md`**, prefer the **local** file for the stack you touched. **Do not** stash long-form system design in those files; use [Documentation/Fitness Platform - System Design.md](../../Documentation/Fitness%20Platform%20-%20System%20Design.md), [fitness-backend/documentation/Backend Design Spec.md](../../fitness-backend/documentation/Backend%20Design%20Spec.md), and stack-local `documentation/system_design.md` when present.

2. **What to add to runbooks** — Short, durable bullets: new commands, scripts, env vars, how to verify, and pointers to the system design docs when readers need architecture context. Do **not** paste full plans or duplicate specs that belong in system design docs.

3. **Edge case** — Pure typo or formatting-only edits may omit runbook updates unless the user asked for commits (then ensure the commit message still describes the change).

This complements **Change communication** (session summaries) with **persistent** context.

